          "body": "The book of Exodus does not end at a destination; it ends with Israel still in the wilderness, still journeying, but now under permanent divine guidance. Verses 36-38 establish the pattern that will govern Israel's movements throughout Numbers: when the cloud lifts, they move; when the cloud rests, they stay. The cloud by day and fire by night — the same sign that led them out of Egypt (13:21-22) — is now anchored to the tabernacle rather than simply preceding the column. God's guidance has become resident among His people. This is not a static presence but a mobile one — the tabernacle is portable precisely so that divine presence can accompany the journey, not merely mark its beginning. The chapter's final phrase, 'in the sight of all the house of Israel, throughout all their journeys,' is Exodus's last word. The book ends not with arrival in the promised land but with the promise of ongoing presence for every stage of the journey not yet taken. This is the comfort of Exodus 40 for the reader: the God who took up residence among Israel is the God who stays."
