        "title": "Divine command structures the space of encounter — the imperative section",
        "range": "40:1-15",
        "excerpt": "Then the LORD spoke to Moses, saying, 'On the first day of the first month you shall set up the tabernacle of the tent of meeting.'",
        "body": "The chapter opens with a divine speech — 'the LORD spoke to Moses, saying' — a formula that has punctuated Exodus since chapter 6 and that the reader now recognizes as the grammar of covenant relationship. God does not merely permit the tabernacle; He commands it, specifies its date of erection, prescribes the exact placement of every furnishing, and mandates the consecration of the priests who will serve in it. The command is structural: six furnishing-placement imperatives (40:2-8) followed by anointing-and-consecration imperatives (40:9-11) followed by priestly ordination imperatives (40:12-15). The sequence is not arbitrary. Furnishings are placed, then consecrated, then servants are appointed. Space, then sanctification, then servants — the same order God follows in creation (space, then sacred objects, then beings who inhabit and tend it).\n\nThe anointing sequence deserves careful attention. Moses is commanded to anoint the tabernacle itself (40:9), then the altar of burnt offering (40:10), then the laver (40:11), and finally Aaron and his sons (40:12-15). The anointing oil (*shemen mishchah*) is the same sacred formula of Exodus 30:22-33, made of myrrh, cinnamon, cane, cassia, and olive oil — a compound God called 'holy anointing oil' and strictly reserved for tabernacle use. The act of anointing transfers these objects and persons from the category of common to the category of holy. The altar is declared 'most holy' (*qodesh qodashim*, 40:10) — the superlative form, the same phrase used of the inner sanctuary. This graduated holiness — altar most holy, priests holy — reflects the logic of Sinai itself, where different zones of the mountain admitted different people (Exodus 19:12-13, 21-24).\n\nThe priestly ordination of Aaron and his sons (40:12-15) is the chapter's most forward-looking element. The 'perpetual priesthood throughout their generations' (*kehunnat olam l'dorotam*) establishes a covenant institution that will survive the wilderness, the conquest, the monarchy, and will not be superseded until the priesthood of Melchizedek order arrives in the person of Jesus Christ (Psalm 110:4; Hebrews 7:11-28). The reader of the whole canon hears, in the Aaronic ordination of Exodus 40, the shadow of the greater Priest who would offer Himself as the sacrifice the altar anticipated.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mishkan* (tabernacle) derives from *shakhan*, to dwell — the same root that appears in verse 35 when the cloud *settles* (*shakhan*) on the tent. God dwells in His dwelling. *Qodesh qodashim* (most holy, 40:10) is the Hebrew superlative by repetition — 'holy of holies' — the same phrase that names the innermost room of the tabernacle and temple. *Olam* (perpetual, 40:15) encompasses indefinite future time, not necessarily eternal — but the Aaronic priesthood did span from Sinai to the cross."
